description.en:
1. Introduction to the course, context and background of European data protection law, differentiating between privacy and data protection, comparison with other regimes of protection of privacy and personal data;
2. Data protection terminology and the key principles of European data protection law;
3. The rules of European data protection law;
4. The data subject's rights and their enforcement;
5. Data transfer rules and Binding Corporate Rules;
6. Applicability of data protection regime and technology;
7. Preparation for the exam.

8. Exam (2,5 h)

description.et:
1. Sissejuhatus ainesse, Euroopa andmekaitse õiguse taust ja kontekst, vahetegu privaatsuse ja andmekaitse vahel, võrdlus teiste privaatsuse- ja andmekaitse režiimidega;
2. Andmekaitse terminoloogia ning peamised printsiibid Euroopa andmekaitse õiguses;
3. Euroopa andmekaitse reeglid;
4. Andmesubjekti õigused ja nende jõustamine;
5. Andmete piiriülese edastuse reeglid ning kontserni sise-eeskirjad;
6. Andmekaitse reeglite kohaldatavus ja tehnoloogia;
7. Ettevalmistus eksamiks.

8. Eksam (2,5 h)

Tests (40% of the final grade): There will be 4 tests in the beginning of 4 seminars which together count for 40% of the final grade. Each test will consist of 10 questions, each question is worth 1 point and will count for 1% of the final grade. The tests will cover the main aspects of the lectures and will be on the topic discussed in the previous lectures.

E - 51%-60% of the answers are correct; the coverage of the subject is poor but sufficient to cover the basics;
D -61%-70% of the answers are correct; the coverage of the subject is logical and associated but lacking in detail;
C - 71%-80% of the answers are correct; the answers are good but the student has not managed to cover all of the topics in sufficient depth;
B - 81%-90% of the answers are corrects; the student has covered the subject very well, created associations between different concepts and built a clear thorough understanding of the subject as a whole. The answers have sufficient detail;
A - 91%-100% of the answers are correct; the student has excellent knowledge of the topic. The answers provide complete overview of what has been asked from the student and clearly indicate that the student has covered all of the materials in sufficient depth.

Written exam (60% of the final grade): The exam will give 60 points, each point is worth 1% of the final grade. The study materials include the GDPR, Handbook, WP Opinions, FAQ, lecture slides, schemes for solving cases under Article 8 of ECHR, all lecture materials of the guest lecturer and seminar materials. Students must be familiar with the GDPR, main concepts of data protection and some of the interpretations which Court of Justice of the European Union and European Court of Human Rights have given in the field of privacy and personal data protection.

E - 51%-60% of the answers are correct; the coverage of the subject is poor but sufficient to cover the basics;
D -61%-70% of the answers are correct; the coverage of the subject is logical and associated but lacking in detail;
C - 71%-80% of the answers are correct; the answers are good but the student has not managed to cover all of the topics in sufficient depth;
B - 81%-90% of the answers are corrects; the student has covered the subject very well, created associations between different concepts and built a clear thorough understanding of the subject as a whole. The answers have sufficient detail;
A - 91%-100% of the answers are correct; the student has excellent knowledge of the topic. The answers provide complete overview of what has been asked from the student and clearly indicate that the student has covered all of the materials in sufficient depth.

resources.mandatory_materials:
1. Regulation (EU) 2016/679 of the European Parliament and of the council of 27 April 2016 on the protection of natural persons with regard to the processing of personal data and on the free movement of such data, and repealing Directive 95/46/EC (General Data Protection Regulation- GDPR);
2. Handbook on European Data Protection Law, European Union Agency for Fundamental Rights, Publication Office of the European Union, 2018, pages 13-180 (also available online on http://fra.europa.eu/en/publication/2018/handbook-european-data-protection-law);
3. Article 29 Working Party opinion 8/2010 on applicable law, adopted on 16 December 2010 (http://ec.europa.eu/justice/policies/privacy/docs/wpdocs/2010/wp179_en.pdf)
4. Article 29 Guidelines on Consent under Regulation 2016/679: (wp259rev.01): http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=623051;
5. Article 29 Data Protection Working Party - Guidelines on the right to "data portability", wp242rev.01 (http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/document.cfm?doc_id=44099);
6. Article 29 Data Protection Working Party - Guidelines on Data Protection Officers ('DPOs'), wp243rev.01 (http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/document.cfm?doc_id=44100);
7. Article 29 Data Protection Working Party - Guidelines on The Lead Supervisory Authority, wp244rev.01 (http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/document.cfm?doc_id=44102);
8. Article 29 Opinion 1/2010 on the concepts of "controller" and "processor": https://ec.europa.eu/justice/article-29/documentation/opinion-recommendation/files/2010/wp169_en.pdf;
9. Article 29 Data Protection Working Party - Opinion 06/2014 on the notion of legitimate interests of the data controller under Article 7 of Directive 95/46/EC.

